European Inflation Has Slided on Food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is first and foremost due to the dizzying rise in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Luxembourg-based Union Statistical Office.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg said.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest rate on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and reduced forced unemployment, would trigger an inflation spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: “negotiating” on inflation so that it doesn’t have to intervene later on.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the twelve-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of fast-paced food and energy prices.
Wheat premiums rose by 88 per cent and soybean premiums reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold as early as last month almost $100 a barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will already drop to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double interest rates in 2008.
Gallup predicts government crisis
After a long stagnation, by the beginning of December the support of the Young Democrats Alliance increased significantly, reaching its peak level since 2002, while the Gallup never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of safe party voters - due to the greater firmness of opposition voters - would mean more than two-thirds (71 percent) support versus a fifth of support for socialists (20 percent).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary scandal: their support within the entire population is 2%.
Among safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low - it has never been higher, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is pretty bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as the next year is concerned, the majority of the population is deteriorating and only one-tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the President of the Government is performing poorly rather than well.
13 percent of respondents trust Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population does not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent does not trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the shaping of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced with the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent estimated that it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, today this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believe that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said it is likely to participate.
By way of comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 percent of the population would participate and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of paying school fees, 79 percent would disapprove of the medical consultation service, and 84 percent would disapprove of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of education fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has fivefold its prices
The average rise in the price level of 16 percent was maintained by the hypermarkets of the Budaörs golden trade triangle, with the difference that VAT has not been raised this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the Budaörs golden trade triangle the Napi newspaper’s usual Christmas basket, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above 1,000 HUF.
Since prices in food supermarkets had already “shot” in December last year, there was no dramatic percentage increase in price compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they can not do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost HUF 6,800.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with redeemable bottle of two liters cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan’s basket it was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora rose by 15, while Tesco and Auchan rose by about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing last year’s most expensive basket values with this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while growth between last year’s cheapest basket and this year’s most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during Christmas last year in prices you felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that shattered trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to apply for each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of circulation of a product, you may lose a significant profit on the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year such extremes did not occur, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer goods grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods, recorded over the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
So for example, besides wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was registered, in the worst case only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic price increase even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the golden trade triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our collected experiences, most of the consumers of the three shops visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, the preserved foods being carried by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, big queues were formed in front of the boxes in all three stores because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that within the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because income falls below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, primarily caused by the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygienic circumstances in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favor infection control, says the doctor-head of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an MRSA contagion was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
An injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after as a result of the infection with MRSA and since then has not been able to perform an important surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, medical department head of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded, of the rest there is no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is exaggerated or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics turn into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and quickly spread under inappropriate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis in the first place in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with weakened organisms, in the elderly or in people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about the infection of MRSA, these infections are everyday in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - Tibor Nyulasi said - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, nursing staff are caring for them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment,” Tibor Nyulasi said.
Hospitalized patients are screened for the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so, infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections in most cases, however current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not fashionable.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when the visible MRSA infections in the patient already occur, said the head of the medical department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict entrustments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and national directives also exist to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of ambulant patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is contagious from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however also in this sense considerable shortcomings are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is contagious through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
What’s more, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favourable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where adequate preventive measures are followed, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol control of police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report on the case of the fatal accident caused by the district police commander of XXII has been made.
The possibility that drove drunk or in a stunned state can be excluded the since resigned commander of the police of district XXII, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passerby - said Friday Attila Morvai, a spokeswoman for the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, after the expert report on the case had been prepared.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary blood alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not drink alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
The then-Chief of the XXII District Police Station, on Tuesday in his private vehicle as he folded into Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII District, hit a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the designated pedestrian area.
(This latter fact, i.e. that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when bending.)
The passer-by lost his life after being hospitalized.
As a result, the district police chief resigned and requested retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The case is being investigated by the Budapest Prosecutor’s Office of Investigation.
Attila Morvai also said the former police commander initially collaborated with prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
€400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total value of 400 million euros to finance infrastructure in education, transport and the environment, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of 300 million euros to finance in the Hungarian budget transport and environmental protection projects, which will be realized from the subsidies of the Cohesion Funds, of which the parties had previously signed a loan contract worth 100 million, the contract they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The EUR 150 million loan agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective of Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million the decision will be taken later, by extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a €50 million contract for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the topic of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalized the details of Metro funding with the EU, they will re-discuss the issue of whether or not to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest rate of the loans is adjusted to EURIBOR and the EIB offers an 8-year grace period, with no fee to keep the loan available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
It is admirable the development of the Bulgarian real estate market - the attention of all Europe is directed towards that Balkan country just mentioned.
What, where and who buy in the EU’s even cheaper market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments on the ski slopes and villas on the beaches.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches of Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Coast of the Sun", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for properties also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts from Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will awaken the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
Likewise, the capital Sofia can be attractive, the commercial and office spaces promise a rapid recovery of the investment.
Bulgaria is on its best way to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, thus being a highlight destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the surroundings of Bansko.
According to analysts, those who buy property in Bulgaria are also striving to change their life and way of living.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot developers are also present and there are traditionally many Russian customers on the Black Sea beaches and in skiing paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, in addition to them the proximity of a big city, shops and usually a local doctor is important.
In the second category are buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in the month of December was included in the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group is real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital property is constantly growing, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these suffered an annual increase of 21 percent
The increase in the price of real estate considerably outweighs the growth of wages.
Fodor and the Six by Hundred Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor the meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue the negotiations at the ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are deliberating on the Ballistic Roadmap, which provides for post-emissions reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in effect until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on the subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to come to an agreement that compared to the 1990 situation, until 2020 the emissions of greenhouse gases responsible for the effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing or unwilling to offer material and technological aid to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the assistance to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
The Six by Hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU pledges to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, from the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed and is willing to commit to a reduction of even 30 percent if the world's other major developed regions and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states pledged to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases by 6 percent over the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with - says the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
There is much that is at stake in Bali, since in two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because otherwise, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new scientific international emission reduction system, whose need was warned in its most recent IPCC report.
As a result, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2oC in Earth’s average temperature could not be prevented, a fact that scientists say would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor post recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
The British Air Force (RAD) first took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar’s general operating corps, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been uploaded to the Internet and their "channel" has already been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defense headquarters" and publishes videos of actions perpetrated in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operations in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to introduce the public to the true purpose of the British army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - said defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, there are also amateur videos on the distributor, for example on the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without presenting however the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet, but the British military is only recently seizing this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with free downloadable shooter video games, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can be put directly in place of the soldiers.
