The party is not always written with red numbers
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers in the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around holidays - which next year will be less - workdays are reorganized.
Even in the EU or in North America the holidays are not unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holidays, state holidays and public holidays.
The festive days are mainly related to religious festivals and historical ephemeris.
We celebrate the New Year also: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is a holiday - the latter especially so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven parties written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15, commemorating the revolution of 1848, and on October 23, commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the foundation of the State, on the 1st of May the feast of labor, on the 1st and 2nd of November we remember our deceased family and friends.
In addition, in our country are two-day feasts the Easter of Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it is often bridged when before or after the party there is only one working day.
In exchange for such extended weekends, during the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the labor minister who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or after the feast.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work continuously even during holidays.
This year the order of work can be altered only around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24 practically stops life in the country, since according to experiences, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First, the agenda around the Labor Day will be modified so that the workers can rest for four consecutive days.
Saturday, April 26 will be working day, so in return Friday, May 2 is a holiday.
The other change relates to the feast of October 23: Saturday, October 18, will have to work instead of Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, the coming year during the holiday of the end of the year will be able to rest, since from the 24th of December almost nowhere will be worked, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
