What insurance does it suit me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver against possible claims, involves a significant expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Having a car is just the beginning.
Choosing the right car insurance is even harder than choosing the vehicle model.
First of all, we need to be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is materialized in an insurance contract, which states that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being held liable for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the insurance price, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use that is given to it, among others.
The insurance companies set their prices based on the statistics, so that the more likely you are to suffer an accident, the higher the fee to be paid.
That is why both women over the age of 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics show that they have a lower rate of injury due to their prudence.
Also, by taking advantage of the counts, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use given to the vehicle will influence the frequency, and thus the likelihood of having some kind of mishap.
As the frequency increases, the odds increase.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
Therefore, the driver must study the situation well to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
Here we will explain the most significant variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that the latter, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers you a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 are faced with various disadvantages when it comes to taking out insurance at an affordable price, such as reduced driving experience and the age of the card.
Although the ideal to be well insured is full-risk insurance, there are other cheaper options.
More cautious drivers can opt for a full-risk franchise, so they get full-risk insurance coverage but at a more feasible price.
This type of agreement would require the client to pay a portion of the amount of the claim.
"The portion of the amount of the claim contributed by the customer will be pre-established based on the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount," says Luis Noguera, chief executive officer in Spain at First Europa, an online insurance broker.
Another option is an extended third-party insurance, so that the customer insures protection against damage caused to third parties, but not against those caused in his own car.
In addition, it would be covered by theft, fire and vehicle loss.
A piece of advice.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid the claims as much as possible, as this will impact on the bonus, and may reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate that the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on that base rate.
"The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and the benefit of the company.
If the company has had a good year, it will be able to afford to increase the bonuses," Noguera explains.
After the age of 25, it is easier for drivers to take out insurance, since the accident rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is most advisable to hire an all-risk franchise.
"Normally young people cannot make use of the experience previously gained when dealing with an accident, and even at the time of driving," says the director in Spain of the European company, adding that most of the accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the 'fear of the novice' has passed.
However, if the client is married but still has no children it is preferable that they negotiate insurance at full risk, as long as their economic situation allows it, of course.
For their part, marriages with children are considered by insurers as the public with the lowest incident rate, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be one at full risk with a deductible (this can be 300 euros), or, when a high level of bonus is available, one to third extended from the third year of life of the vehicle.
“They drive more relaxed and have a greater purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchise,” said Luis Noguera.
For retirees it is advisable to have a full-risk insurance with a franchise (which is 150 euros), or an extended one to third parties when you have a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver against possible accidents, but also because it represents a significant expense, which is why it is essential to properly study the insurance that suits us best according to our personal situation.
