Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that hasn't been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
Three decades ago, researchers suspected that there could be rays on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays call from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, tells Cris Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to Urey-Miller’s famous model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, gave rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there were life there someday, that would have to be in one of the earliest states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500°C reign, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Possibly, Venus is a 'diabolic' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest research findings to be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the well-known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers also discovered in the southern polar region a swirling cloud vortex.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of Giuseppe Piccioni researchers from the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called Dawn Star or Evening Star orbits the Sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar does not resemble Earth much, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
The two planets had agglomerated water that remained on Earth in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
